Halloween is not traditionally celebrated in Ethiopia, as it is a Western holiday that originated in Europe and was popularized in the United States. However, Ethiopia does have its own unique celebrations and traditions around the time of the harvest moon, which typically falls in September or October.

During this time, Ethiopians celebrate the Meskel festival, which commemorates the discovery of the True Cross by Saint Helena, the mother of Emperor Constantine. As part of the celebration, Ethiopians traditionally eat a dish called "Doro Wot", which is a spicy chicken stew made with onions, garlic, ginger, and spices.
